= Getting help with ImageJ =

== Use the mailing list ==

The '''''very best''''' way to get help with ImageJ is to subscribe to the [[Mailing Lists|ImageJ mailing list]]. There are over 2000 subscribers, with many experts on both scientific and technical topics.

The ImageJ community firmly believes in [[Open Source]], including public discussion of the software. In this way, each question benefits not only the one asking, but everyone subscribed to the lists, and everyone who subsequently does a web search on the same topic, thanks to the [http://list.nih.gov/archives/imagej.html mailing list archives].

== Reporting bugs ==

If you encounter a bug, please consider taking some time to [[Report a Bug]] and test our fixes. Remember: ImageJ is a community effort, and it will be as good as you make it.

== Other ways to get help ==

* For real-time chat, you can often find the ImageJ and Fiji developers on [[IRC]].
* For video tutorials, please see the [http://youtube.com/fijichannel Fiji YouTube channel].
* Some people like to [http://stackoverflow.com/questions/tagged/imagej post about ImageJ on Stack Overflow], a programming Q&A site.

= Getting help regarding the ImageJ Wiki =

If you look for help editing this Wiki, please look [http://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Help:Contents here].

== Tips ==

* To be able to edit a page, you need to log in. If you do not have an ImageJ Wiki account yet, [{{SERVER}}/wiki/index.php?title=Special:Userlogin&type=signup register via email].
* To edit a new page, enter the title in the search box; there will be a red link you can follow to edit the page.
* If you see a page having a layout you want to imitate, pretend to edit that page, copy the respective markup code (cancel editing after you copied it), and paste it into the page where you want to have it.

